3. Prompt 2 — Step-by-Step Feature Guide
Prompt used: Create a step-by-step guide for creating and managing tasks using the priority scoring system. Target audience: Beginners.

Guide: Creating and Managing Tasks by Priority
This guide walks you through creating tasks, setting priorities, adding tags, and using the scoring system to stay on top of your most urgent work.

Prerequisites
•	Python 3.8+ installed on your computer
•	Task Manager cloned and terminal open in the TaskManager folder
•	You should see: PS C:\...\TaskManager> in your terminal

Step 1 — Create your first task
python cli.py create "Fix homepage bug" -p 3 -u 2026-06-17
You should see: Created task with ID: a3f8c2d1-xxxx
Write down the first 8 characters of your ID — you will need it for the next steps!

Step 2 — Create a second task with lower priority
python cli.py create "Update profile page" -p 2 -u 2026-06-25

Step 3 — List all tasks
python cli.py list
You will see both tasks with priority symbols:
!    = Low
!!   = Medium
!!!  = High
!!!! = Urgent

Step 4 — Start working on a task
python cli.py status <your_task_id> in_progress
Replace <your_task_id> with the first 8 characters from Step 1.

Step 5 — Add a blocker tag to boost priority score
python cli.py tag <your_task_id> blocker
This adds +8 points to the task's importance score! Tags must be lowercase.

Step 6 — Check for overdue tasks
python cli.py list -o
Any tasks past their due date appear here. These get +35 bonus points in the scoring system.

Step 7 — Mark a task complete
python cli.py status <your_task_id> done
The task is now stamped with a completion timestamp and its score drops by 50 points.

Step 8 — View your statistics
python cli.py stats
Shows totals by status, priority level, overdue count, and tasks completed in the last 7 days.

Common Mistakes to Avoid
•	Forgetting the -u flag means no due date — task won't appear in overdue lists
•	Using wrong date format — always YYYY-MM-DD, not DD/MM/YYYY
•	Tags must be lowercase — 'Blocker' won't trigger the +8 score boost
•	Copying the full UUID instead of just the first 8 characters

Troubleshooting
Problem	Solution
Task not found	Run list to find the correct ID
Date rejected	Use YYYY-MM-DD format exactly
Tag not boosting score	Make sure tag is all lowercase
Status update fails	Check valid statuses: todo, in_progress, review, done

4. Prompt 3 — FAQ Document
Prompt used: Create a comprehensive FAQ for beginners new to command-line tools, focusing on getting started, core features, and troubleshooting.

Getting Started
Q: Do I need to install anything extra?
A: No! Task Manager only uses Python's built-in libraries. As long as you have Python 3.8 or higher, you are ready to go.
Q: How do I know if Python is installed?
A: Open your terminal and type: python --version. If you see a version number, you are good. If not, download Python from python.org.
Q: Where are my tasks saved?
A: In a file called tasks.json in whatever folder you run the app from. It is created automatically when you add your first task.
Q: How do I see all available commands?
A: Run python cli.py with no arguments and it will print a full list of commands with descriptions.
Q: Do I need an internet connection?
A: No — everything runs locally on your computer. Tasks are saved to a file on your disk, not in the cloud.

Core Features
Q: What do the priority numbers mean?
A: 1=Low, 2=Medium (default), 3=High, 4=Urgent. Higher numbers get more attention in the automatic priority scoring system.
Q: What is the difference between priority and score?
A: Priority is what YOU set manually. Score is what the app calculates automatically based on priority, due date, tags, and recent activity. Two HIGH priority tasks can have very different scores depending on their deadlines.
Q: Can I change a task's status back to TODO after marking it done?
A: Yes — run: python cli.py status <id> todo. However, the completed_at timestamp will remain from when it was originally marked done.
Q: What tags get a score boost?
A: Only these three exact lowercase tags: blocker, critical, urgent. Each adds +8 points to the task score. Other tags are stored but do not affect scoring.
Q: What happens if I forget to set a due date?
A: The task still works normally. It just won't appear in overdue lists and won't receive due date bonus points in the scoring system.
Q: How does the priority scoring system work?
A: Each task earns a score based on: priority level (10-60 pts), due date urgency (up to +35 pts), completion status (up to -50 pts), special tags (+8 pts), and recent activity (+5 pts). Higher scores appear first when sorting by importance.

Troubleshooting
Q: I get 'python is not recognized' — what do I do?
A: Try python3 instead of python. On some systems Python 3 is installed as python3 rather than python.
Q: My task ID is very long — do I need the whole thing?
A: No! Commands only need the first 8 characters of the ID. You can see these in the list output next to each task.
Q: I deleted a task by mistake — can I get it back?
A: Unfortunately no — deletion is permanent. Always double-check the task ID before running the delete command.
Q: The app says 'Task not found' but I can see the task in list — why?
A: You may have copied the wrong ID. Task IDs are case-sensitive — copy carefully from the list output, or use only the first 8 characters shown.
Q: Can two people use the same tasks.json file at the same time?
A: Not safely — simultaneous writes could corrupt the file. For shared task lists, use separate files and the merge feature to combine them periodically.
Q: My tasks.json file seems corrupted — what do I do?
A: Open tasks.json in a text editor and check it is valid JSON. If it is broken, you may need to delete it and start fresh — unfortunately there is no built-in backup system.

